text: Heart breaks for the senseless tragedy in Kentucky. May God comfort and keep.
Nothing means more to me than making sure we take care of our military‚Äôs needs as they fight a war we can‚Äôt afford to lose.  Today, we took a giant step forward in that direction.
Winning is ensuring we have the funding needed for our military to meet the tremendous challenges they face.
Ending the government shutdown stops the losing for the country.  But it‚Äôs not winning.  Winning is solving the nation‚Äôs problems.
I‚Äôm convinced that to continue the government shutdown ‚Äî after this proposal ‚Äî does more harm than good to our effort to find common ground.
I'm hopeful my Democrat colleagues will find a way to reopen the government so we can find a solution on immigration, defense spending, and many other important issues.

I'm very pleased to hear Majority Leader McConnell commit to the Senate that if we do not make a breakthrough on immigration by February 8th, the Senate will take the issue up under regular order. 

This is a more than reasonable proposal by the Majority Leader.

President Trump has expressed a desire to have border security with compassion on immigration. #winningcombination.

General Kelly is tough but reasonable.  

Some other staff in the White House hold extreme and unrealistic views.

It's time to stop the madness.  Vote for a CR through February 8. It will allow us to reach a deal on all outstanding issues including immigration.

text: I know it looks like a mess ‚Äî- but there are many senators of good will who want to solve the problem. I appreciate Sens. Portman, Whitehouse, Coons, Alexander, Collins, Murkowski  and others' commitment to hard work and finding solutions last night.
In light of these realities, I‚Äôm hopeful there will be overwhelming bipartisan support for the February 8 proposal
Military necessity ‚Äîcombined with the reality that DACA recipient lives will soon be turned upside down ‚Äî provides the incentive for Congress to get it right once and for all.
General Mattis‚Äôs statement yesterday that defense cuts and continuing resolutions have done more damage to the American military than any enemy on the battlefield was very sobering.

After my discussions with numerous senators on both sides of the last night it is clear to me a commitment to move to immigration after February 8th is the key to ending the government shutdown and finding resolution on all the outstanding issues.

This will guarantee the Border Security/DACA issue will be brought forward with an open amendment process for resolution no later than February 8th. I‚Äôm confident we can find a solution to Border Security/DACA once we start the process.

After extensive discussions with senators, I believe such a proposal would pass if there was a commitment that after February 8th the Senate would move to an immigration debate with an open amendment process if no alternative agreement was reached with the White House and House.
I also agree with Senator McConnell we are close to a resolution on all these issues.

Leader McConnell mentioned last night he was willing to make a proposal for a CR through February 8 and seek resolution on immigration, disaster relief, military and government funding, CHIP, and other health care related issues.  I would support such a proposal.

@DeptofDefense We could easily pass a continuing resolution ‚Äì which lasts days (certainly more than the four proposed by the Senate Minority Leader) and less than the 30 days passed by the House of Representatives ‚Äì to close the deal on outstanding issues which remain.

Continuing resolutions are devastating to our military. 

As @DeptofDefense Gen Mattis said this morning - no enemy in the field has done more to harm the readiness of the U.S. military than the combination of defense spending cuts and continuing resolutions.

He‚Äôs exactly right.
Simply put, there‚Äôs no reason to shut the government down and no reason to continue this chaos for the next 30 days.

Our military, which desperately needs additional funding as they are already scraping by, doesn‚Äôt win.  

American people who expect the government to be functioning and operating don‚Äôt win.

Cynicism about the ability of Congress & Pres to solve problems increases even further.

Everyone is convinced they‚Äôll win ‚Äì but in reality, nobody wins in a government shutdown.  

The ‚Äòblame game‚Äô makes for great Washington theater, but doesn‚Äôt serve the needs of the nation.
